Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/laying/hasLayingPerson
Object: Relates an act of laying a paper to the person laying it.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/laying/Withdrawal
Object: The act of withdrawing a paper previously laid before a House.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/laying/lays
Object: Relates an act of laying a paper to the paper which has been laid.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/laying/
Object: A model describing the process of laying papers before a House and any subsequent withdrawal and replacement.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/laying/hasHouse
Object: Relates an act of laying or withdrawing a paper to the House in which the paper is laid or withdrawn.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/laying/withdraws
Object: Relates an act of withdrawing a paper to the paper which has been withdrawn.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/laying/hasLayingAuthority
Object: Relates an act of laying a paper to a laying authority.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/laying/LayingAuthority
Object: The authority under which a paper is laid before a House. Legislation may impose a duty on a body to lay papers before a House, these are laid 'by Act'. Command papers are laid in a House by the government and are laid 'by Command'. A paper is laid in the House of Commons or House of Lords either 'by Act' or 'by Command'.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/laying/Laying
Object: The act of making available a paper and any supporting documents into a House. Papers may be laid before both Houses on the same day.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/laying/WithdrawnPaper
Object: A paper withdrawn after having been laid. Papers or documents forming part of a bundle may be individually withdrawn.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/laying/LayingDuty
Object: The duty of a body to lay papers before a House as imposed by an Act of Parliament.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/laying/Session
Object: The period during which Parliament is convened. The first session of a parliament begins on the same day as the parliament period: this date is given in the dissolution proclamation at the end of the previous parliament. The session ends on the day set in a subsequent prorogation proclamation. Subsequent sessions within the parliament period begin and end on dates set in subsequent prorogation proclamations. The last session of a parliament ends with prorogation followed by dissolution. Session periods are the same for both Houses.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/laying/LayingOrWithdrawal
Object: The act of laying a paper before a House or withdrawing a paper from a House.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/laying/replaces
Object: Relates a laid paper to the withdrawn paper being replaced.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/laying/laidOn
Object: Relates an act of laying a paper to the date on which the laying occurs. This date falls within a parliamentary session or prorogation period, and not during a dissolution period.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/laying/LaidPaper
Object: A paper having been laid before a House. Papers and supporting documents may be laid as a bundle.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/laying/House
Object: A parliamentary House, for example: the House of Lords.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/laying/hasLayingBody
Object: Relates an act of laying or withdrawal a paper to the laying body laying or withdrawing it.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/laying/LayingBody
Object: A body competent to lay papers before a House or Houses.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/laying/hasLayingDuty
Object: Relates an act of laying a paper to a duty to lay papers under an Act.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/laying/withdrawnOn
Object: Relates an act of withdrawal of a paper to the date on which the withdrawal occurs. This date falls within a parliamentary session or prorogation period, and not during a dissolution period.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/laying/hasSession
Object: Relates an act of laying or withdrawing a paper to the session which the paper is laid into or withdrawn from. Papers laid during a prorogation period are considered laid into the session which has been prorogued.
